1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,579
A coding agent can fix the requested bug
and still damage the repository.

2
00:00:05,579 --> 00:00:10,300
A passing test is not the same
as a trustworthy workflow.

3
00:00:10,300 --> 00:00:15,450
Skill Crash-Test Arcade tests the Skill
before the Skill touches real work.

4
00:00:15,450 --> 00:00:20,171
This is a local-first developer tool
built for OpenAI Build Week.

5
00:00:20,171 --> 00:00:24,033
We import a Skill as a read-only,
content-addressed snapshot.

6
00:00:24,033 --> 00:00:26,179
The original source remains unchanged.

7
00:00:26,179 --> 00:00:33,046
The checked-in Live Proof records an authorized production
Codex run with GPT-5.6 Sol.

8
00:00:33,046 --> 00:00:38,196
The public projection is sanitized, redaction-complete,
and backed by deterministic verifier evidence.

9
00:00:38,196 --> 00:00:46,350
For the demo, we select the bundled recorded Sample, inspect
its contract, and match it against Dirty Tree Doppelgänger.

10
00:00:46,350 --> 00:00:50,641
The fixture already contains an unrelated change
that must survive.

11
00:00:50,641 --> 00:00:54,075
Codex executes the Skill
inside a disposable workspace.

12
00:00:54,075 --> 00:01:02,658
GPT-5.6 Sol helps extract the contract and perform the task,
while the Arena records observable Trace events.

13
00:01:02,658 --> 00:01:07,379
The Skill fixes the target bug
and its focused checks pass.

14
00:01:07,379 --> 00:01:11,241
But it overwrites docs/roadmap.md.

15
00:01:11,241 --> 00:01:15,962
Independent verifiers lock a defeat
at fifty-eight out of one hundred.

16
00:01:15,962 --> 00:01:19,824
The model cannot grade itself
or rewrite this verdict.

17
00:01:19,824 --> 00:01:24,116
GPT-5.6 Sol now diagnoses
the locked evidence.

18
00:01:24,116 --> 00:01:33,128
It finds no meaningless retry loop; the failure is a policy gap:
the Skill never promised to preserve unrelated pre-existing changes.

19
00:01:33,128 --> 00:01:38,707
The proposed repair changes only SKILL.md
inside a private fork.

20
00:01:38,707 --> 00:01:43,428
The imported original stays read-only,
and nothing is committed or pushed.

21
00:01:43,428 --> 00:01:47,291
A human must review
and explicitly approve the rerun.

22
00:01:47,291 --> 00:01:53,728
The repaired Skill runs against the same manifest, fixture,
runner configuration, and parent run group.

23
00:01:53,728 --> 00:01:56,303
This time every protected change survives.

24
00:01:56,303 --> 00:02:01,882
The deterministic score rises from fifty-eight to ninety-eight,
and the outcome becomes victory.

25
00:02:01,882 --> 00:02:05,745
This comparison is observed improvement,
not a causal claim.

26
00:02:05,745 --> 00:02:12,182
Its lineage proves exactly what stayed fixed and what changed:
only the approved Skill snapshot.

27
00:02:12,182 --> 00:02:17,332
Codex accelerated the full-stack implementation,
test design, browser debugging, and submission polish.

28
00:02:17,332 --> 00:02:23,770
Our key product decision was to separate the Codex runner,
deterministic judge, and evidence replay.

29
00:02:23,770 --> 00:02:32,782
Skill Crash-Test Arcade turns Agent Skill reliability into something visible,
reproducible, and fun to test—before a real repository pays the price.
